# Building

NiFi is a complex Maven codebase. Never build code (testing or otherwise) using javac.
Always use `mvn` instead, or preferably the `.mvnw` wrapper script.

Additionally, building a maven module using the also-make flag (`-am`) is often very
expensive and slow. Instead, only build the specific module you are modifying. Assume that
the user has already built the entire codebase and that only the specific module you are
modifying needs to be built again. If this fails, you can prompt the user to build the entire
codebase, but only after you have attempted to build the relevant modules yourself first.
It is important not to run `mvn clean` at the root level or at the `nifi-assembly` level without
the user's express permission, as this may delete a running instance of NiFi, causing permanent
loss of flows and configuration.

When preparing to run system tests, packaged runtime artifacts must be refreshed using
`mvn clean install` on the relevant packaging modules. Do not rely on `mvn install` or
`mvn package` alone for system tests, as stale NARs or assemblies may be reused.

If a change affects code packaged into a NAR, rebuild the packaging module that delivers that
code before running system tests. For example, changes under
`nifi-framework-bundle/nifi-framework/nifi-web/...` require rebuilding
`nifi-framework-bundle/nifi-server-nar`, because the runtime uses `nifi-server-nar` to deliver
the updated web application classes.

Before running tests in `nifi-system-tests/nifi-system-test-suite`, refresh its runtime assembly
with `mvn clean install` for that module as well. The system test runtime uses
`target/nifi-lib-assembly`, which is populated in `pre-integration-test` and later phases, so
running `mvn test` or `mvn package` alone may leave stale runtime contents in place.
